article.description:
Rookie Seimone Augustus tied a season-high
with 32 points to help the Minnesota Lynx beat the Phoenix Mercury
94-82 on Sunday.
article.headline: Augustus pours in 32 as Lynx snap skid vs. Mercury
article.linkText: Augustus pours in 32 as Lynx snap skid vs. Mercury
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio stresses the
importance of winning at home. Her team was listening on Sunday.

Rookie Seimone Augustus tied a season-high with 32 points to
help the Minnesota Lynx beat the Phoenix Mercury 94-82.

Nicole Ohlde added 22 points and Tamika Williams grabbed 12
rebounds as the Lynx (5-6) snapped a two-game skid and bounced back
from Friday's 30-point loss in San Antonio.

"We need to take advantage of playing at home," McConnell
Serio said. "Playing on the road in this league is drastically
different. I was hoping we'd feel embarrassed after that thrashing
in San Antonio and come back to get a win at home."

Diana Taurasi led the Mercury (3-6) with 23, but was 7-for-22
from the field and was visibly frustrated by her team's rebounding
struggles and Minnesota's pestering defense. Cappie Pondexter added
22 points for the Mercury.

"They set a pattern of really beating us on the boards,"
Phoenix coach Paul Westhead said. "I don't know what hurt us more,
the lack of rebounding or poor shooting, but initially it was the
rebounding problem."

The Lynx led 29-16 after the first quarter, outrebounding
Phoenix 18-6, and getting 10 second-chance points.

"That was key for us," Augustus said. "Any time you rebound
well, good things are going to happen."

Minnesota extended its lead to 42-24 in the second quarter
before the Mercury closed to within 10 with 1:15 to play. Augustus
scored five of the next seven points to give the Lynx a 52-39
halftime lead. The Lynx shot 53 percent in the first half and
outrebounded Phoenix 26-13.

Minnesota outrebounded Phoenix 43-27 for the game.

Ohlde scored six straight points for Minnesota to start the
second half and put the game out of reach. Any signs of Phoenix
making a run were stopped by an Augustus basket in traffic or
another Lynx offensive rebound.

"Augustus does a lot where she just breaks down her defender
and gets those little runners in the lane," Westhead said. "She's
very tough to defend."

Minnesota plays four of its next five on the road, where it is
1-4. Williams said the key to improving on the road is keeping
everyone involved offensively.

"Tonight, everyone got some," she said. "We need to keep
everyone moving and put pressure on the other team when we're on
the road."

Sunday's game was also the first meeting between Rookie of the
Year candidates Augustus and Pondexter. Both teams downplayed the
one-on-one matchup.

"I knew all the hype coming into this game," Augustus said.
"After Friday, I just wanted a win."

"I don't think there was any special emphasis tonight,"
Westhead said. "Our team didn't have a good offensive night. We'll
play better and (Pondexter) will help us play better."
